SIMPLE: reputation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reputation
<hw>Rep`u*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(-t?"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧putation</ets>, L. <ets>reputatio</ets> a reckoning,
consideration. See <er>Repute</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The estimation in which one is held; character in
public opinion; the character attributed to a person, thing, or action;
repute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The best evidence of <qex>reputation</qex> is a man's whole
life.</q> <rj><qau>Ames.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The character imputed to a person
in the community in which he lives. It is admissible in evidence when he
puts his character in issue, or when such reputation is otherwise part
of the issue of a case.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Specifically: Good reputation; favorable regard;
public esteem; general credit; good name.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I see my <qex>reputation</qex> is at stake.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The security of his <qex>reputation</qex> or good name.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Account; value.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[/Christ] made himself of no <qex>reputation</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Phil. ii. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Credit; repute; regard; estimation; esteem;
honor; fame. See the Note under <er>Character</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reputatively</ent>⟦br⟧
